<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM37700 - Approval of schemes:
Scheme rules relating to alterations</h1>
<br>
<p>Paragraph 42 does not provide for an automatic loss of approval
in the event that an alteration is made to the scheme rules that
would not be capable of approval, however this would constitute a
&ldquo;disqualifying event&rdquo; and approval may be withdrawn
under paragraph 42 (1).
<br>
<br> The normal procedure to be followed is for proposed
alterations to be submitted to ESSU for review and if capable of
approval then an approval letter issued in a standard format
advising that the approval of the alterations will come into effect
on the date that they are adopted by the company. If the
alterations have already been adopted by the company then the
alterations will be approved from the date of the HMRC letter
approving such amendments.
<br>
<br> ESSU require companies, where appropriate, to provide in

their scheme rules that &ldquo;no amendment to a &ldquo;key

feature&rdquo; of the scheme shall take effect until it has been

approved by HM Revenue and Customs</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">except that, in operating such rules,

resolutions may express alterations</li>
</ul>
<div style="margin-left: 2em">
<ul>
<li class="dash">to be subject to HMRC approval being received,

or</li>
<li class="dash">not to take effect until approved by HMRC,</li>
</ul>
</div>
<p>so that the date HMRC approval is given is the date that the

alteration takes effect</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">Where an amendment is made subject to

conditions and these conditions are never met e.g. HMRC approval

then the amendment will never come into effect. If an amendment

never comes into effect then this would not constitute a

disqualifying event.</li>
</ul>
<p>Some older schemes already approved provide that &ldquo;no

amendment/alteration shall be made to the scheme without the prior

approval of HMRC or the Board of Inland Revenue&rdquo;.

<br>
<br> As HM Revenue and Customs does not approve alterations

(under paragraph 43) before they have been made, the operation of

such rules can cause practical difficulties and lead to

misunderstandings. If new schemes are received containing such

wording, scheme advisors should encourage the use of the wording as

in the above.

<br>
<br> Schemes may be approved which provide that no amendment

shall take effect unless approved by HMRC, although they can also

cause practical difficulties. In particular, practical difficulties

may arise because, in the interval between the making of the

amendment and Revenue approval to it being given or refused, it

will not be known what the effective scheme rules are.

<br>
<br> Before accepting schemes containing &ldquo;unless&rdquo;

provisions, scheme advisors should therefore ensure that the

company concerned is aware of the practical difficulties, if the

company wishes to proceed, seek to have the practical difficulties

minimised by requiring the scheme rules to provide that HMRC should

be notified immediately amendments are made.

<br>
<br> If resolutions make amendments which are expressed not to

take effect unless approved by HM Revenue and Customs and</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">HMRC approval is subsequently given to

such an amendment, the date from which it takes effect is the

earlier date on which it was made by the passing of the relevant

resolution</li>
<li class="filledcircle">HMRC approval is never given to such an

amendment, it never becomes effective. In these circumstances

scheme advisors may accept that it will not constitute a

disqualifying event</li>
</ul>
